title: Grateful Dead Live at Nassau Coliseum on 1981-05-09
lineage: NAK-700's > SONY TC-D5M  Dolby On, FOB
description: Mississippi Half Step-> Franklin's Tower-> Feel Like A Stranger, Bird Song-> Little Red Rooster, Candyman, Mama Tried-> Mexicali Blues, Looks Like Rain-> China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider Lost Sailor-> Saint Of Circumstance-> Ship of Fools, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> Nobody's Fault But Mine-> Truckin'-> Black Peter-> Around & Around-> One More Saturday Night, E: Brokedown Palace

reviews.review_text: sweet and sleepy Such a lovely show. Jerry in shining form, pouring out everything from the very start of half step. The show is effortless and brimming with energy. The recording is good considering how bad nassau typically sounds. As far as 81's setlists and performance, you're hard pressed to top this.

Still Awesome This was my first show and I still have the tape I acquired in '82 of this show.  It wasn' until many shows later that I could appreciate the quality of this show. Combining this material with the 5/6 show release would have painted a great picture of the dead in '81 - before Bobbyy's "HAAH!" years.  It rates a 4 with a little eq'ing.

Turn it up and see This show deserves much more love than it has gotten. As with most of the audience recordings from the larger arenas, things sound distant and dull played at low volume. But as you turn it up, all the various sounds coming out of those giant speaker stacks come into play. On the other hand, if you turn some of the soundboards too much things get shrill pretty quick. (Perhaps one of the experienced tapers can explain the dynamics of this) At any rate this show is upbeat, punchy, tight and sounds great played outdoors loud on a summer day.

Front row Went to this show with my friend "Bulk" from SUNY Brockport. Front row - right. Only time I was front row for a Dead show. Truly killer show. 

One of my favorite memories was this giant doobie I had rolled using multiple papers. Had to be 6" long. Jerry looked over and smiled as I/we partook. Ha! 

Estimated was transcendent. Guess you had to be there ... Slept in a broom closet in the Port Authority later that night after missing the last Red & Tan bus to New City, NY. Great memories.
